This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

CONDITIONS:
MODIFIED ON 06/16/22:  COURT WILL ALLOW THE DEFENDANT TO USE THE INTERNET AND ELECTRONIC DEVICES WITH A CAMERA FOR REMOTE SEX OFFENDER TREATMENT AND EVALUATION.

CONDITIONS MODIFY ON 03/15/2022:  The Court orders the defendant to use and possess a cell phone without a camera and with Bluetooth and internet disabled.  The Court orders the defendant to use a Roku device for entertainment streaming. It should be noted that the Roku device does not have any features that allow for chatting or any other type of communication. The defendant would use streaming services such as Netflix, Hulu, Apple TV, etc. and not stream any explicit or illegal content.  The Court orders the defendant to use a Garmin GPS device that comes preloaded with maps and does not access the internet nor have any chat features.

PREVIOUS CONDITIONS:
Defendant is not to have any possession of any device that is capable of contacting the internet with the exception of what he needs to provide his work products and only at his work location (EXCEPT FOR THE ABOVE CONDITIONS).  Defendant to have no use or possession of any file sharing networks, with the exception of work and while at his work location.  Defendant prohibited from using any device that captures an image.  Defendant is prohibited from accessing any child exploitation material and any other sexually explicit material through the Internet or by any other means.  Defendant prohibited from contacting a minor over the internet or using a website to gather information about a minor. Defendant is prohibited from intentionally deleting any history from any computer or device that accesses the Internet. Defendant prohibited from using any application where the content automatically deletes upon the recipient opening the content.  Defendant to have no unsupervised contact with any child under the age of 18.
